TITLE: Research - Health - World Health Organisation Reference Centre in Melbourne - A ferret is infected with influenza for virus identification at the World Health Organisation Reference Centre for Influenza, operated by the Australian Commonwealth Serum Laboratories in Melbourne.  Animals are used in the production of new anti-sera, in testing possibly new virus strains against existing anti-sera, and in testing new anti-sera against known virus types. Report On Operations in Solomon Islands - [Black and white photographic print of] Japanese camp at LUNGA. Buildings were of timber covered with palm fronds for camouflage. Tents were of green canvas. The camp was in pleasant healthy surroundings with refrigeration and reticulated water supply - [sub-item]

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photograph of] underground concrete shelter under construction at the LUNGA camp. It was probably intended as a command post and communications centre. The walls are battened from the bottom outwards - [sub-item]

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photograph of] the Lunga lagoon. Typical of lagoons found along the grassy plain area of Guadalcanal. In the foreground is a Jeep. These machines did very good work - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photograph of] water-borne sewerage scheme at Kukum camp. The latrines open off a bridge across the Kukum River which carries the sewage towards the sea. In the rear is a view of the Japanese camp at KUKUM - [sub item].
Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photograph of] Japanese RDF installations sited near Guadalcanal airfield were captured intact and ready for use - [sub item].
Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photograph of] Japanese RDF installations sited near Guadalcanal airfield were captured intact and ready for use - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] the control building of distinctly Japanese architectural design, here shown under construction on a small hill overlooking the airfield and surrounding areas. It is constructed  of coconut trunks and saw timber with galvanised iron roof. It was ceiled with a material similar to Celotex. It is now in use by the American Air Units for control purposes - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] the control building of distinctly Japanese architectural design, here shown under construction on a small hill overlooking the airfield and surrounding areas. It is constructed  of coconut trunks and saw timber with galvanised iron roof. It was ceiled with a material similar to Celotex. It is now in use by the American Air Units for control purposes - [sub item].
Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] runway looking East. It was constructed of 6" of river gravel covered by 2" of decomposed coral rock - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] runway looking West. It proved necessary to cut the clump of trees immediately opposite end of runway. Note shacks used by construction troops and electric light installation. Typical US Marine in foreground - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] view showing splinterproof pens for large aircraft. Three were  nearing completion and were constructed of coconut logs internally with sandbags externally. No attempt had been made at comouflage  - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print of] the taxiway leading to the splinterproof pens was finished with coral stabilised with cement giving concrete finish to the river gravel pavement - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print]. The Japanese construction methods were somewhat primitive. In the foreground are scarifiers made of timber with iron spikes fixed therein - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print.] Considerable earthwork was carried out on the runway in order to secure a level grade. The rollers shown were captured from the enemy. In the distance are the splinterproof workshops. Note electric lighting for night construction work - [sub item]. - [sub item].

Report On Operations in Solomon Islands. [Black and white photographic print.] Splinterproof workshops under construction south of the runway. The roof is 1" steel supported on double steel trusses of small rise. The trusses rest on timber trestles which are to be filled in with sandbags. The roof is later to be covered with 2 layers of sandbags and camouflaged. The span is approximateley 50' and the structures were evidently intended for fighter aircraft - [sub item].
